.SH FEATURES
.SS Interactive execution mode
Prefixing a subcommand with the interactive flag \f[CR]\-i\f[R] executes
the command interactively.
.PP
In interactive mode:
.IP "1." 3
The command\(cqs Markdown is rendered to the terminal as rich text
support.
.IP "2." 3
If any flags or options are specified in the spec, Inkjet will prompt
the user for those parameters.
.IP "3." 3
The user will be given the option to execute the step or preview the
code block.
.IP "4." 3
Required parameters will have \(lq*\(rq.
If a default exits it will be shown in the prompt.
Hitting enter will select the default.
.PP
Interactive execution mode is useful for tutorial guides or when you are
not sure what options or flag parameters are required.
.SS Preview mode
Prefix a subcommand with the preview flag \f[CR]\-p\f[R] to extract code
from the specified task\(cqs code block.
If \c
.UR https://github.com/sharkdp/bat
bat
.UE \c
\ is available, it will be used to pretty print the block with syntax
highlighting using your installed theme.
This mode is also useful for copying the block into the pasteboard:
\f[CR]inkjet \-p build | pbcopy\f[R].
.SS Shell completions
Inkjet can generate completions for your shell dynamically.
In this way, you\(cqll get helpful tab completions depending on the
Markdown file.
See the \f[CR]completions\f[R] folder for the bash and fish scripts.
For example the fish script calls
\f[CR]inkjet inkjet\-dynamic\-completions fish | source\f[R].
Your shell may cache results in the short term but generally you can
navigate to different folders and get project\-specific
shell\-completion.
.SS Positional arguments
These are defined beside the command name within
\f[CR](round_brackets)\f[R].
They are required arguments that must be supplied for the command to
run.
An argument may be made optional by including a question mark:
\f[CR](optional_arg?)\f[R].
The argument name is injected into the script\(cqs scope as an
environment variable.
Defaults can be set with an equals sign: \f[CR](port=8080)\f[R].
An arg with a default is naturally optional as well.
.PP
\f[B]Example:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
## test (file) (test_case?)

> Run tests

\f[BI]\(ga\(ga\(gabash\f[R]
echo \(dqTesting $test_case in $file\(dq
\f[BI]\(ga\(ga\(ga\f[R]

## serve (port=8080)

\f[BI]\(ga\(ga\(ga\f[R]
\f[BI]python \-m SimpleHTTPServer $port\f[R]
\f[BI]\(ga\(ga\(ga\f[R]
.EE
.SS Infinite arguments
An argument can be made to accept infinite arguments by including three
dots: \f[CR](extra...)\f[R].
It can be made optional by including a question mark.
This is best left for the last argument.
Infinite args are collected as a space\-separated string, perfect for
shell expansion.
.PP
\f[B]Example:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
