\f[BI]\(ga\(ga\(ga\f[R]
.EE
.SS Named flags
You can define a list of named flags for your commands.
The flag name is injected into the script\(cqs scope as an environment
variable.
If a flag name includes a \f[CR]\-\f[R] it will be replaced with an
underscore (i.e.\ \f[CR]\-\-no\-color\f[R] becomes \f[CR]no_color\f[R])
.PP
It is important to note that \f[CR]inkjet\f[R] always injects a very
common \f[CR]boolean\f[R] flag called \f[CR]verbose\f[R] into every
single command even if it\(cqs not declared.
This saves a bit of typing for you!
This means every command implicitly has a \f[CR]\-v\f[R] and
\f[CR]\-\-verbose\f[R] flag available.
Like all \f[CR]boolean\f[R] flags, the value of the \f[CR]$verbose\f[R]
environment variable is either \f[CR]\(dqtrue\(dq\f[R] or simply
unset/non\-existent.
.PP
\f[B]Example:\f[R]
.IP
.EX
## serve

> Serve this directory

\f[I]<!\-\- You must define OPTIONS right before your list of flags \-\->\f[R]
\f[I]<!\-\- Bold is used here for readability but is not required \-\->\f[R]

**OPTIONS**

\- port
  \- flag: \-p \-\-port
  \- type: string
  \- desc: Which port to serve on
  \- required

\f[BI]\(ga\(ga\(gash\f[R]
