.SS Directives
You can change how parsing occurs by including some special directives
in the Markdown file.
Most of the time, I don\(cqt use these but they are available to you for
advanced use cases.
.SS inkjet_sort: false
By default, subcommands in the help output are listed in the same order
they are defined in the Markdown file.
Users can decide to instead have subcommands sorted alphabetically by
defining this directive.
As an example, if you are using inkjet to distribute a CLI of code
snippets, sorted help would make sense.
For projects, you may want the order to be as defined (e.g., publish
comes after test).
.SS inkjet_fixed_dir: false
When you run an inkjet command from a project subdirectory, inkjet will
by default search up the tree to find an \f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] file.
In order for commands to work as expected, scripts execute as if their
working directory was the same as the location of the
\f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] file that defined them.
Similarly, if you call Inkjet with
\f[CR]\-\-inkfile tests/inkjet.md\f[R], your commands will execute as if
the working directory was \f[CR]tests\f[R].
If this is not desired, simply include the
\f[CR]inkjet_fixed_dir: false\f[R] directive in the file to have the
working directory match your current directory.
.SS inkjet_import: all
It\(cqs often the case that large projects will have multiple
\f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] files.
For instance, each service may have its own \f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] file to
define how to build and test that component.
To enable the import feature, include the text directive
\f[CR]inkjet_import: all\f[R] somewhere within your main
\f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] file.
If Inkjet discovers this directive in the text, it will find all other
\f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] files within the current folder and merge them
together before parsing and building out the command tree.
If the imported file has a H1 heading, its commands will appear as a
subcommand of that heading.
If only H2 and below headings are available in the imported file, those
commands will become sibling commands for the parent.
See a merged example here.
.PP
The merge behavior is as follows:
.IP "1." 3
Locate \f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] files and files ending in
\f[CR].inkjet.md\f[R] within the current folder.
.IP "2." 3
Found \f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] files are first sorted by directory depth and
then alphabetically.
.IP "3." 3
Merged definitions can override previously defined definitions.
.PP
The override behavior is useful as it enables you to share generic
commands, and then override the generic on a project\-by\-project basis.
.PP
All imported \f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] files are run as if they were called
directly.
Namely, if \f[CR]inkjet_fixed_dir\f[R] is not set to false, imported
commands will run with their working directory set to the parent
directory of its \f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] file.
.PP
