.SH ENVIRONMENT
Inside each script\(cqs execution environment, \f[CR]inkjet\f[R] injects
a few environment variable helpers.
Scripts inherit the environment from your shell.
.PP
\f[B]\f[CB]$INK\f[B]\f[R]
.PP
This is useful when running inkjet within a script.
This variable allows us to call \f[CR]$INK command\f[R] instead of
\f[CR]inkjet \-\-inkfile <path> command\f[R] inside scripts so that they
can be location\-agnostic (not care where they are called from).
This is especially handy for global inkfiles which you may call from
anywhere.
.PP
\f[B]\f[CB]$INKJET\f[B]\f[R]
.PP
This is similar to \f[CR]INK\f[R] above, except it always resolves to
the original \f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] file.
For instance, You may have some common scripts in the project\(cqs main
\f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] file and call those scripts in imported
\f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] files throughout the project.
Note that if you call the imported inkfile directly, it will resolve the
same as \f[CR]$INK\f[R] above.
For this reason, you will see different behavior depending on where you
call the script.
.PP
\f[B]\f[CB]$INK_DIR\f[B]\f[R]
.PP
This variable is an absolute path to the inkfile\(cqs parent directory.
Having the parent directory available allows us to load files relative
to the inkfile itself, which can be useful when you have commands that
depend on other external files.
.PP
\f[B]\f[CB]$INKJET_DIR\f[B]\f[R]
.PP
This is much like \f[CR]INK_DIR\f[R] except it always resolves to the
main \f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] file\(cqs parent directory.
.PP
\f[B]\f[CB]$INKET_IMPORTED\f[B]\f[R]
.PP
A helper utility that is set to \(lqtrue\(rq if the script was imported
by another \f[CR]inkjet.md\f[R] file.
.PP
\f[B]\f[CB]$NO_COLOR\f[B]\f[R]
.PP
Inkjet respects NO_COLOR to disable colorized output for its own
commands.
